<P>
JURY BEING CHOSEN FOR OIL SPILL TRIAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An Alaska judge refused to dismiss charges against former Exxon Valdez captain 
Joseph Hazelwood and ordered jury selection to begin in Anchorage for his trial 
in the nation's worst oil spill. 
</P>
<P>
His attorneys argued that he should not be tried in a state court because 
federal law preempts state law in such cases. The Exxon Valdez ran aground on 
March 24, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil into Alaskan waters; 
the cost of cleaning it up has been estimated at $2 billion. Hazelwood faces a 
felony charge of criminal mischief and various misdemeanor charges, including 
being intoxicated. 
</P>
