<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 8; Column 2; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
105 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
EARNINGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Boeing Co.: The Seattle-based aerospace firm's 1989 net income rose 58% over 
the previous year to $973 million. 
</P>
<P>
Revenue jumped 19.5% to $20.3 billion. The 1989 results include $298 million 
attributable to an accounting change for income taxes. Fourth-quarter sales 
remained essentially flat at $4.8 billion, but earnings tumbled 55% to $77 
million. The company said the 48-day strike by the International Assn. of 
Machinists &amp; Aerospace Workers caused delivery delays, cutting 
fourth-quarter sales by about $2 billion. The company also cited 
higher-than-anticipated lump-sum wage payments and strike disruption costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
