<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
SUPPORT FOR FAMILY PLANNING BILL URGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
County Supervisor Harriett M. Wieder urged support of a state bill Monday that 
would restore most of a recent, $24-million cut in state assistance to family 
planning centers. 
</P>
<P>
Wieder told a crowd of about 100 people at Leisure World that "you are going to 
be missionaries" to help pass AB 99, an effort to restore $20 million to the 
family planning budget. 
</P>
<P>
"You are going to be the squeaky wheel that gets the attention of legislators." 
</P>
<P>
Gov. George Deukmejian's proposed budget unveiled Jan. 10 would slice more than 
$1 billion in services to the poor. In Orange County, the family planning 
budget dropped from $500,000 to about $86,000 with the cuts, Wieder said. 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody is looking at what the loss incurred by these cuts will be in the long 
run," she said, adding that the budget reductions "could create $190 million in 
additional costs." 
</P>
<P>
Assembly Bill 99 was written by 31st District Assemblyman Bruce Bronzan 
(D-Fresno). 
</P>
</TEXT>
