<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: SCIENCE/TECHNOLOGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Compiled by Jonathan Weber, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Marketing Agreement: Despite the troubles it has experienced over the past 
several years, IBM still can give a big lift to small companies. Network 
Software Associates of Laguna Hills, which specializes in designing software 
for the complex computer networks used by IBM's biggest customers, has signed a 
marketing agreement with Big Blue that it hopes will boost sales. 
</P>
<P>
Network Software already works closely with IBM, as it must to sell the 
specialized networks that allow IBM personal computers and terminals to "talk" 
with larger minicomputers and huge mainframes. And the 10-year-old, privately 
held firm has made a good business of it, building up to a staff of 50. 
</P>
<P>
Now, the company will be an official "industrial application remarketer" for 
certain IBM products. And though the agreement won't have a huge impact on the 
way the firm does business, "having the IBM logo next to yours ensures an image 
of strength in the customer's mind," a company spokeswoman said. Compiled by 
Jonathan Weber, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</TEXT>
