<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIXTH COUNTRY FREEZES NORIEGA'S ESTIMATED $20 MILLION IN ASSETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Authorities in six nations have frozen $20 million in "liquid assets" 
associated with deposed Panamanian Gen. Manuel A. Noriega, the Justice 
Department said today. 
</P>
<P>
Austria became the sixth country to freeze bank accounts associated with 
Noriega, said David Runkel, a spokesman for the attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
The action was taken at the request of the United States, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Runkel also doubled his previous estimate -- from $10 million to $20 million -- 
of money in the various bank accounts that the U.S. government believes is 
associated with illegal drug activity by Noriega. 
</P>
<P>
The five other countries where bank accounts associated with Noriega have been 
frozen are France, Switzerland, West Germany, Luxembourg and the United 
Kingdom, Runkel said. 
</P>
<P>
"These are liquid assets -- mostly bank accounts," Runkel told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
The American invasion of Panama produced a number of documents that have aided 
in the investigation of Noriega's assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
